<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA021689-0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 19183 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
February 16, 1989, Thursday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
San Gabriel Valley; Part 9; Page 1; Column 5 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1329 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
GROUP FILES LAWSUIT TO HALT GRAND AVE. EXTENSION PROJECT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEFFREY MILLER, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
DIAMOND BAR 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Residents opposing the extension of Grand Avenue from Chino Hills have tried 
lobbying officials and staging demonstrations in attempts to prevent or delay 
an influx of traffic into Diamond Bar. Now they are going to court. 
</P>
<P>
The Stop Grand Avenue Expressway Committee and five of its members filed suit 
this week against San Bernardino County, seeking an injunction blocking the 
opening of the extension, which is scheduled for late next month. The committee 
is one of two Diamond Bar citizens groups that oppose the extension because 
they believe it will create gridlock in their community. 
</P>
<P>
Grand Avenue now ends at the Los Angeles-San Bernardino county line. However, 
road crews are working rapidly in western San Bernardino County to link Grand 
Avenue with Chino Hills, a community where rapid growth and geographic 
isolation have caused serious traffic problems. 
</P>
<P>
The suit, filed Tuesday in San Bernardino County Superior Court, alleges that 
San Bernardino County is to blame for much of Chino Hills' congestion. The 
plaintiffs argue that the county's construction of roads and other 
infrastructure improvements have failed to keep pace with residential 
development as required by the Chino Hills Specific Plan. 
</P>
<P>
More than 30% of the 26,000 homes planned for the Chino Hills are already in 
place, but only 10% of the roadwork envisioned in the Specific Plan to improve 
access to the area has been completed. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Funnel Commuters 
</P>
<P>
Because of this lag in road construction, the plaintiffs argue, the extension 
of Grand Avenue would funnel thousands of Chino Hills commuters through Diamond 
Bar, which already has enough traffic woes of its own. The suit asks that the 
extension be delayed until other road projects to serve the area are completed. 
</P>
<P>
"We're going to have a tenfold increase in traffic because they decided to 
build one road instead of 10," said plaintiff Gary Lawson, founder of the Stop 
Grand Avenue Expressway Committee. "We don't want to be the scapegoat for the 
county of San Bernardino because (officials) didn't do their job." 
</P>
<P>
San Bernardino County Chief Deputy County Counsel Craig Jordan said his office 
had not been served with the suit and could not comment. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
'Solid Ground' 
</P>
<P>
However, San Bernardino County Supervisor Larry Walker, who represents Chino 
Hills, said he has been advised by the county's lawyers that the extension 
project is not in danger. 
</P>
<P>
"I've been assured repeatedly that we're on solid legal ground in every aspect 
of it," Walker said. "The lawsuit may have the positive impact of clarifying 
the issue. There are a lot of clouds over the project. I think it will be a 
good thing to have those issues explained." 
</P>
<P>
Walker said he sees a contradiction in the suit's premise. 
</P>
<P>
"On the one hand they're saying (San Bernardino County officials) are bad 
because they didn't build the infrastructure, and on the other hand they're 
saying they want to stop an infrastructure project," he said. "I'll tell the 
judge, 'Yes, your honor, you're darned right we're behind in infrastructure. 
Grand Avenue is our first major step toward catching up.' " 
</P>
<P>
Gary Miller, founder of the Concerned Citizens for Diamond Bar Traffic Control, 
a citizens committee that has competed with Lawson's group for the support of 
Diamond Bar residents, said he doubted that the lawsuit would be successful. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
'Doesn't Make Sense' 
</P>
<P>
"They're going to go before a judge and say, 'We want Chino Hills to build 
roads, but not this road," Miller said. "I'm for anything that'll work. But 
this doesn't make any sense." 
</P>
<P>
Vivian T. Shallito, attorney for the Stop Grand Avenue Expressway Committee, 
said the suit rests on the county's violation of its own Specific Plan for 
Chino Hills. 
</P>
<P>
"They're straying from the Specific Plan that they worked long and hard on for 
the Chino Hills," Shallito said. "In the plan there were 10 roads to be built. 
Only two (including Grand Avenue) have been done. . . . They're actually 
amending (the plan) by default, and if you amend it you have to start the 
process all over again." 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Two-Lane Road 
</P>
<P>
The suit argues that San Bernardino County is also violating the plan by 
opening Grand Avenue as a two-lane road instead of a four-lane expressway. The 
county is doing this, the suit alleges, as part of its efforts to open the road 
before March 7, when Diamond Bar voters decide whether their community should 
become a city. Some opponents of the extension believe that a Diamond Bar City 
Council would be more aggressive in trying to stop the project than Los Angeles 
County has been. 
</P>
<P>
"They have people working two shifts, seven days a week to get that road 
completed before we vote for cityhood," Lawson said. 
</P>
<P>
Walker sharply disagreed with this claim, saying that only a small portion of 
Grand Avenue will be two lanes when the road opens in late March. When 
construction is completed by April 28, the entire road will be four lanes wide 
with a raised median, he said. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Schedule Accelerated 
</P>
<P>
Walker confirmed that the work schedule for construction of the road has been 
accelerated, but said this was to compensate for delays caused by recent rains, 
not to finish the project before Diamond Bar incorporates. 
</P>
<P>
"These people are virtually making stuff up," Walker said of the plaintiffs. 
"The fact that they're blatantly wrong on some basic facts may discredit them 
in their lawsuit. . . . These are people who have decided what happened and 
every fact that comes along that doesn't fit what they believe, they ignore 
it." 
</P>
<P>
At the same time that Diamond Bar voters choose whether to become a city, they 
will also be able to elect the first City Council. With the campaign for five 
council seats heating up, some questioned whether the timing of filing the suit 
-- three weeks to the day before the election -- was coincidental. Three of the 
five individuals plaintiffs -- Lawson, Donna Rhode and Benjamin Quan -- are 
running for council seats. 
</P>
<P>
"Is this a lawsuit or publicity?" said Miller, who also is a candidate for the 
City Council. 
</P>
<P>
Walker refused to comment on the plaintiffs' motives, but said: "The fact that 
Diamond Bar people want to use this for politics is not objectionable. When 
they distort the facts, that's objectionable." 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Council Slate 
</P>
<P>
Lawson, however, said the lawsuit was not politically motivated and that its 
timing was determined by the need to block the extension project before the 
road opens. But at a news conference Tuesday announcing the filing, the 
plaintiffs urged that voters elect Lawson, Rhode and Quan as a council slate to 
protect Diamond Bar from Chino Hills traffic. 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles County Supervisor Pete Schabarum has not seen the lawsuit and will 
not comment until he has read the complaint, said Judy Hammond, the 
supervisor's press deputy. 
</P>
<P>
Schabarum and Walker met Tuesday, but were unable to reach agreement on Grand 
Avenue. Schabarum insisted that mitigation measures such as other roads serving 
Chino Hills be completed before the road opens. Walker argued that Chino Hills 
residents need the road opened as soon as possible, Hammond said. 
</P>
<P>
The prospect of Diamond Bar cityhood complicates the controversy. Schabarum has 
been advised that the county's jurisdiction over Diamond Bar would end 
immediately if voters choose cityhood on March 7, Hammond said. What remains 
unclear is whether Los Angeles County could continue to insist upon mitigation 
measures after jurisdiction over the area changes, she said. 
</P>
<P>
Miller said he believes Schabarum will not permit the road to open before San 
Bernardino takes steps to alleviate the influx of Chino Hills traffic into 
Diamond Bar. Lawson said his group wants the new City Council, if there is one, 
not Los Angeles County, to negotiate with San Bernardino County,. 
</P>
<P>
"The county of San Bernardino is not complying with the Chino Hills Specific 
Plan, and the county of Los Angeles is sitting idly by," Lawson said. "Two 
county governments are playing God and the people of Diamond Bar don't have a 
say in anything." 
</P>
</TEXT>
