<HEADLINE>
<P>
LUXURY LINER RAMS ANCHORED NAVY SHIP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A 400-foot luxury liner attempting to dock in the Port of Palm Beach Wednesday 
night hit an anchored Navy ship and tore several holes in the 110-foot vessel, 
the Coast Guard said. 
</P>
<P>
The accident involving the Viking Princess and the unnamed naval cargo loading 
craft caused no serious injuries to passengers or crew, Coast Guard Petty 
Officer Jerry Snyder said. 
</P>
<P>
"It's a very small harbor," with only two shipping channels and a small area 
where the cruise liners have to turn around, Snyder said. 
</P>
<P>
Two Coast Guard utility boats plugged three holes below the Navy vessel's water 
line, and minor flooding was quickly brought under control, Snyder said. 
</P>
<P>
Some passengers of the Viking Princess were shaken up, but the crew was able to 
care for them without assistance, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
