<P>
FAMILY GETS $35,000 IN BRUTALITY CASE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Long Beach City Council has approved a $35,000 settlement for a family that 
sued the city alleging police brutality and illegal entrance of their home by 
officers. 
</P>
<P>
The council, meeting in closed session, approved the settlement for William 
Westland, his wife and his two sons, Assistant City Atty. Robert Shannon said. 
Following a disagreement during a traffic stop, officers allegedly went to the 
Westland home in Long Beach, where a fight ensued and Westland and his sons 
were arrested. Westland also alleged he was beaten by officers en route to 
jail. 
</P>
<P>
Westland pleaded guilty to disturbing the peace. But the sons were never 
prosecuted and, as part of the settlement, the city stipulated that they should 
not have been arrested, said E. Thomas Barham, attorney for the Westlands. 
</P>
