AT&amp;T said it plans to cut long-distance rates on 1.6% April 1 to offset a 
30-cent increase in local phone bills starting the same day. The changes will 
mark the last step in a cost shift ordered by the Federal Communications 
Commission that reduces prices that long-distance carriers pay local phone 
companies for completing calls while adding a monthly "subscriber line charge" 
to local bills. That charge will increase to $3.50 in April. The FCC must still 
approve AT&amp;T's proposed plan for passing on its cost savings. AT&amp;T said 
