<HEADLINE>
<P>
REGIONAL HEADQUARTERS FOR WELLS FARGO; 
</P>
<P>
TOWER IN KOLL CENTER PLANNED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MICHAEL FLAGG 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wells Fargo Bank gave the Koll Co. a boost when it said it would move into a 
planned 16-story building just north of the San Diego Freeway in Koll Center 
Irvine. 
</P>
<P>
The bank signed a 15-year lease for nearly $30 million, and the building will 
now be called Wells Fargo Tower. 
</P>
<P>
That will make Koll's lenders happy, since they can be assured of one large 
tenant even before the $85-million building has been built. Construction starts 
this month. 
</P>
<P>
The bank took 71,000 square feet of space on floors 7 through 9. 
</P>
<P>
The bank will consolidate its regional offices -- now in the Irvine Co.'s 
Newport 
</P>
<P>
Center -- and other operations near John Wayne Airport. Altogether, nearly 300 
employees will move. 
</P>
<P>
The building -- designed by local architects Langdon Wilson Mumper -- will be 
the fourth tower Koll has constructed in the business center, which extends on 
both sides of the freeway. The giant Newport Beach-based developer plans to 
build three more office towers, one more low-rise office building and a third 
hotel. 
</P>
<P>
Koll's partners on the new tower -- scheduled for completion in April, 1990 -- 
are Hart Advisors Inc. of Hartford, Conn., and Columbia Savings &amp; Loan 
Assn. in Beverly Hills. MICHAEL FLAGG 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Map, Koll Center Irvine; Drawing, Rendering of planned 16-story building in 
Koll Center Irvine 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
