<P>
ONE COUNT AGAINST CAPTAIN DROPPED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SUBIC BAY NAVAL BASE, Philippines 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A U.S. Navy judge today dismissed one of three charges against the captain of a 
Navy vessel who is accused of abandoning Vietnamese refugees who later resorted 
to cannibalism to survive. 
</P>
<P>
Capt. James A. Freyer, the presiding judge, said there was not enough evidence 
to support the charge that the USS Dubuque skipper, Capt. Alexander G. Balian, 
failed "to render assistance" to a Vietnamese refugee who allegedly drowned 
while trying to swim to the ship. 
</P>
<P>
Balian, 48, of Los Angeles, also is charged with ordering crewmen to prevent 
refugees from climbing aboard the Dubuque. In a third charge containing 11 
specifications, the judge today dropped one that alleged failure to provide 
necessary medical supplies. 
</P>
